title: Build ORT by default for Mac OS X versions 10.12+
body:
This change has 2 components:

1) Build MacOS shared library with minimum target MacOS version set to 10.12. Previously, it was defaulting to 10.14 as the build agent had a MacOS version of 10.14
 
2) The Python wheel needs to have its platform tag manually overridden so that it can be downloaded on a pre-10.14 machine. In an ideal world, the cmake change alone should have been enough forcing the platform tag on the wheel to be installable on any 10.12+ machine. But the wheel project has a logic that doesn't allow the platform tag to be anything less than the minimum MacOS version that the Python interpreter itself is built for. See here - https://github.com/pypa/wheel/blob/a51977075740fda01b2c0e983a79bfe753567219/src/wheel/macosx_libfile.py#L364. This means that we would have to manually override the platform tag (in build.py) so as to achieve what we want. 

Resolve #2354

title: Improve node and node argument name generation

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
This PR adds the efforts in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3638 to master branch. This change has two benefits.

- it ensures the uniqueness of names at graph level.
- it avoids the change of names when possible. This is quite annoying if ORT keep renaming variables when, for example, adding a new graph transformer.

Q: Why we don't use a global naming manager?
A: 

- If we move the name generator out of graph, there will be two places we check if a name is usable: 1) inside graph's name-generating functions 2) inside name manager's name generator. This is error-prone and largely reduces readability.
- Having a global name manager implies that manager knows all the names. However, the implication is not correct. The global name manager is not aware of pre-stored names such as initializer names in ONNX model.
- The above two points may be resolved with a 10x large change. Basically, every places which uses names need to be replaced with some functions in the global name manager.

title: PrepareForReduce in_dim != 0 was false -- unsure how to approach fixing this
body:

Here is the error:
`
2020-04-24 09:26:49.8288396 [E:onnxruntime:, sequential_executor.cc:183 onnxruntime::SequentialExecutor::Execute] Non-zero status code returned while running ReduceMax node. Name:'' Status Message: [...]\onnxruntime\onnxruntime\core\providers\cpu\reduction\reduction_ops.cc:266 onnxruntime::PrepareForReduce in_dim != 0 was false. Can't reduce on dim with value of 0 if 'keepdims' is false. Invalid output shape would be produced. input_shape:{0,4}
`

My initial thought is this is due to their being no predicted bounding boxes for a given input (and thus the "input shape" that is trying to be reduced has the shape `input_shape:{0,4}`?

Any ideas?

title: Set gradient as output only for easy mode
body:
Currently gradients are added to graph outputs by default. This causes extra memory usage that cant be reused for the outputs. 
Gradients are specifically required as outputs for easy mode, so setting the config accordingly will save memory (same amount as the static model size).

title: Remove internal work item links.
iOS cross build on MacOS
body:
**Description**: Enable iOS cross build on MacOS

**Motivation and Context**
The current iOS cross build (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3298) runs on Linux, the problems with it, 
1. Requires complicated tool chain setup
2. Does not currently build iOS simulator, you cannot create iOS CI from the arm/arm64 binary
3. Cannot easily switch target OS version (ios12, ios13, ...)

The motivation is to use XCode to build iOS on MacOS, since most iOS developers will have Mac as dev machine.
Enabled in this PR
- X86_64 iphonesimulator
- Arm64 iphoneOS

Also enabled building use XCode on MacOS
This will not remove the iOS cross build on linux, that part will be kept unchanged

Usage,
On MacOS, Install latest XCode, run
./build.sh --config Debug --ios --ios_sysroot iphonesimulator --osx_arch x86_64 --apple_deploy_target 13 --skip_test --use_xcode

Not yet addressed,
1. Build arm/arm64 binary. will add it later,

title: Dependency issues with Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb
body:
Hi,

We are having issues with .NET core 2.2 web projects referencing Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime (1.2.0).
The web projects is hosted in Azure as an app service (Microsoft.Web/sites).

The nuget package has a dependency for Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb, and since we remove all .pdbs before we publish to cloud, the web app crashses with a 502.5 error code.

Solutions we've found:
- Leaving the _\bin\runtimes\win-x86\Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb_ (obviously)
- Removing the _\bin\runtimes\win-x86\Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb_ reference from the *deps.json file

We'd rather not keep a .pdb that is over 50 Mb per runtime project referencing the nuget, and we haven't found any other solution to the *deps.json reference than removing it post build with Powershell.

_We also see some very large files in \bin\runtimes\ for osx and linux, which we of course can remove post build, but it feels a bit odd that the runtimes directory is over 600 Mb for some dependencies._ Edit: realized this is most certainly on us for not publishing to a specific runtime/framework in TeamCity.

Also tested around with [ExcludeAssets settings](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/consume-packages/package-references-in-project-files) in the *.csproj / nuget reference without any luck.

This is a related issue / solution we found:
https://github.com/klalle/Microsoft.ML.onnxruntime_UWP_fix

So basically we _can_ solve the issue, but would like to know the reason for the .pdb dependency, and what your recommendations / solution to the above is? It's not an issue we've ever had with other Nuget packages.

Kind regards,
Emil
